        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our primary goal is to detect 158 μm [CII] line of a z=6.96 galaxy IOK-1 at S/N &gt;= 5 as well as detect (if not detected, constrain) its FIR continuum flux at S/N &gt;= 3. The [CII] line is redshifted to λ = 158 μm (1 + z) ~ 1.26 mm, and this galaxy has a compact size ~ 0.54" in rest frame UV (see Figure 1 in Science Justification). Hence, we will use Band 6 with an angular resolution = 1.3" (more than twice the size in UV) to cover [CII] line and FIR continuum around 1.26 mm in case they are more extended than UV light. We have observed IOK-1 in [CII] and FIR continuum with ALMA in Cycle 0. We could not detect FIR continuum but marginally detected possible [CII] line at S/N = 3.2 level (see Figure 3 in Science Justification). The sensitivity we reached in Cycle 0 was 1σ = 0.2 mJy/beam for [CII] line with a velocity resolution of 40 km/s and an angular resolution of 1.27" × 0.87". To detect [CII] line with at least S/N = 5 in Cycle 2, we request a sensitivity of 1σ = 0.2 × 3/5 = 0.12 mJy/beam with a velocity resolution = 40 km/s and an angular resolution = 1.3". We input this into “Time Estimate” of ALMA Cycle 2 Observing Tool (OT), using a frequency width of 40 km/s and a resolution of 1.3" for a Point Source. We obtain 10.22 hours including calibrators and overheads (5.39 hours on source).
     Now, we set the Integration Time = 5.39 hours (time on source for S/N=5 detection of [CII] in IOK-1), Observing Frequency = 238.76 GHz, Bandwidth per Polarization = 7.5 GHz and Number of Antennas = 34, Resolution = 1.3" in the ALMA Sensitivity Calculator. We obtain the 1σ sensitivity of 0.00782 mJy for the FIR continuum observation. UV to FIR SED of IOK-1, including our ALMA Cycle 0 3σ upper limit on FIR continuum flux (54 μJy/beam), is similar to SEDs of local dwarf irregular galaxies that have dust temperature of 29.27 K and dust emissivity index of 1.5 on average when fitted by a modified black body (MBB). Normalizing this MBB with the 1σ sensitivity flux of 0.00782 mJy and integrating it from 8 to 1000 μm, we obtain 1σ sensitivity in total IR luminosity L(FIR, 1σ) = 6.2 × 10^9 Lsun. Meanwhile, local and low-z star-forming galaxies tend to have luminosity ratio of log L([CII])/L(FIR) ~ -2.5 as seen in Figure 4 left panel (triangles: normal galaxies, green asterisk: z=1-2 SF). Using this luminosity ratio and [CII] luminosity of IOK-1 (6.3× 10^7 Lsun.) estimated from our tentative S/N=3 detection in Cycle 0 (See Figure 3), total IR luminosity of IOK-1 is L(FIR, IOK-1) = 2.0 × 10^10 Lsun. Hence, we will be able to detect/constrain FIR continuum of IOK-1 at S/N = L(FIR, IOK-1)/ L(FIR, 1σ) ~ 3.2 level. 
     We have proposed to observe IOK-1 in Cycle 1, and it will be transferred to Cycle 2 if the observation does not complete in Cycle 1. However, in this Cycle 2 proposal we request better sensitivities and more than twice lower angular resolutions than those we requested in Cycle 1. Hence this proposal does not duplicate our Cycle 1 program transferred to Cycle 2 (see also section II of Science Justification).</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
