        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We would like to detect 158 μm [CII] line of a z=7.215 galaxy SXDF-NB1006-2 at S/N ≥ 5 as well as detect (if not detected, constrain) its FIR continuum flux at S/N ≥ 3. The [CII] line is redshifted to λ = 158 μm (1 + z) ~ 1.28 mm, and this galaxy has a compact size ~ 0.81" in rest frame UV (estimated from the relative size difference between this galaxy in NB1006 image and IOK-1 in NB973 and F125W images). Hence, we will use Band 6 with an angular resolution = 1.6" (about twice the size in UV) to cover [CII] line and FIR continuum around 1.28 mm in case they are more extended than UV light. Figure 5 in Science Justification shows [CII] luminosity L([CII]) vs. star formation rate SFR for local star forming galaxies and z &gt; 6 Lyα emitting galaxies (LAEs). De Looze et al. (2011) found a correlation for local star forming galaxies. We plot SFR ranges of a z=6.96 LAE IOK-1 (our another target) and a z=6.56 LAE HCM6A by adopting SFRs estimated from their UV continua SFR(UV) as lower limits and SFR(UV) plus SFRs estimated from total IR luminosity L(FIR) upper limit SFR(FIR) as upper limits. L([CII]) and SFR(FIR) of IOK-1 are from our ALMA Cycle 0 observation (see Figure 3). Two different SFR(UV) of IOK-1 are from Ota et al. (2010, red data point) and Ono et al. (2012, green data point). IOK-1 and HCM6A are slightly shifted from the local correlation. If a correlation with a similar slope holds at z &gt; 6, it could look like the red or green line in the figure. The blue data show SFR(UV) of our target z=7.215 LAE SXDF-NB1006-2 and imply that L([CII]) of this LAE could be in the magenta shaded range; that is, log L([CII] erg/s)=41.6 – 41.9. The most severe case log L([CII] erg/s)=41.6 converts to S([CII]) = 0.417 mJy for 200 km/s velocity width. To detect [CII] line at S/N=5 with 40 km/s velocity resolution (the same as the case of IOK-1) and an angular resolution = 1.6", we request a sensitivity of 1σ = 0.417*sqrt(200/40)/5 = 0.19 mJy/beam in Cycle 2. We input this into “Time Estimate” of ALMA Cycle 2 Observing Tool (OT), using a frequency width of 40 km/s and a resolution of 1.6" for a Point Source. We obtain 4.53 hours including calibrators and overheads (2.44 hours on source).
     Now, we set the Integration Time = 2.44 hours (time on source for S/N=5 detection of [CII]), Observing Frequency = 231.35 GHz, the Bandwidth per Polarization = 7.5 GHz and Number of Antennas = 34, Resolution = 1.6" in the ALMA Sensitivity Calculator. We obtain the 1σ sensitivity of 0.01219 mJy for the FIR continuum observation. UV to FIR SED of our another target z=6.96 LAE IOK-1, including our ALMA Cycle 0 3σ upper limit on FIR continuum flux (54 μJy/beam), is similar to SEDs of local dwarf irregular galaxies that have dust temperature of 29.27 K and dust emissivity index of 1.5 on average when fitted by a modified black body (MBB). Assuming z=7.215 LAE SXDF-NB1006-2 is also similar to dwarf galaxies, normalizing this MBB with the 1σ sensitivity flux of 0.01219 mJy and integrating it from 8 to 1000 μm, we obtain 1σ sensitivity in total IR luminosity L(FIR, 1σ) = 1.0 × 10^10 Lsun. Meanwhile, local and low-z star-forming galaxies tend to have luminosity ratio of log L([CII])/L(FIR) ~ -2.5 as seen in Figure 4 left panel (triangles: normal galaxies, green asterisk: z=1–2 SF). Using this luminosity ratio and [CII] luminosity of SXDF-NB1006-2, log L([CII]erg/s)=41.6 (see above), total IR luminosity of this galaxy is L(FIR, SXDF-NB1006-2) = 3.3 × 10^10 Lsun. Hence, we will be able to detect/constrain FIR continuum at S/N = L(FIR, SXDF-NB1006-2)/ L(FIR, 1σ) ~ 3.3 level.
     We have proposed to observe SXDF-NB1006-2 in Cycle 1, and it will be transferred to Cycle 2 if the observation does not complete in Cycle 1. However, in this Cycle 2 proposal we request better sensitivities and more than twice lower angular resolutions than those we requested in Cycle 1. Hence this proposal does not duplicate our Cycle 1 program transferred to Cycle 2.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
