    <prp:abstract>Probing star formation and physical properties of galaxies from local to early Universe including epoch of reionization (EoR) at z &gt; 6 is key to revealing how galaxies formed and reionization progressed with cosmic time. While these properties of low-z galaxies have been well studied using CO lines, those of EoR galaxies have not due to their faintness. 158 μm [CII] can be a powerful alternative to detect EoR galaxies, as it is the strongest cooling line of interstellar medium (ISM) in galaxies and observable in mm at z &gt; 6. We propose ALMA observations of [CII] and underlying dust continua of two galaxies at z=6.96 and z=7.215, because they are two of the highest redshift objects in EoR and we have many data for comparison with ALMA observations. We will investigate relation between high-z and local star-forming galaxies, obscured star formation and reionization state at z~7-7.2, dynamics and states of ISM of EoR galaxies. We observed the z=6.96 galaxy in Cycle 0 leading to possible 3σ marginal [CII] detection and nondetection of continuum. Refining sensitivity and resolution, in Cycle 2 we will definitively (≥ 5σ) detect [CII] and see if we also detect continua from EoR galaxies.</prp:abstract>
